It is worse yet when our great men go upon the stage and flght in the arena, choosing disgrace (183-210). Many were Nero's crimes; but it was worst of all when he sang in theam-es, and strove for the parsley crown (211-230). Catilina and Cethegus were free-born ; Cicero was ignoble, yet he won a greater victory than Octavius. Marius, too, and the Decii, and the last good king, were of lowly birth; a slave saved the city, when the consul’s sons would have betrayed it (231-268).
